    "text": "Section I: Periodic Health Examination\n3\nI.C Diabetes Mellitus\n \nFigure 3: Algorithm for Diabetes Mellitus Screening\nN.B: Ministry of Health recommends measuring glycemia yearly in people with ≥35years \nI.D Lipids Disorders \nScreening guidelines for lipids disorders differ among experts. Cholesterol disorders \nscreening is recommended in adult men aged ≥35 years, in women aged ≥40 years or \nmenopausal and All adults with any of the following conditions regardless of age: \nAssess Comorbidities \n   • Diabetes \n   • Cad\n   • Previous CV Event\n   • Atherosclerosis \n   • Aneurysm \n*Any = High Risk\nTreat to the target \nCalculate & Categorize \nCV Risk \nCalculate using Framingham \nhttps://www.mdcalc.com/calc/38/\nframingham-risk-score-hard-coronary-\nheart-disease \n• Low risk : < 10%\n• Moderate risk : 10%- 19% \n• High risk :>20%\nOBTAIN FASTING LIPID \n            Baseline\n            Annually \n               Determine Lipid Targets \nLDL-C:\n  • Optimal: <100 mg/dL\n  • Near or above optimal: 100-129 mg/dL\n  • Borderline high: 130-159 mg/dL\n  • High: 160-189 mg/dL\n  • Very high: ≥190 mg/dL.\nTotal cholesterol:\n  • Desirable: <200 mg/dL\n  • Borderline high: 200-239 mg/dL\n  • High: ≥240 mg/dL.\nTriglycerides:\n  • Normal: <150 mg/dL\n  • Borderline high: ≥150-199 mg/dL\n  • High: 200-499 mg/dL\n  • Very high: ≥500 mg/dL\n \nIs the patient Aged ≥ 35\n                     or\nAged ≥ 18 and overweight or obese with at least 1 risk factor*\nNO\nReevaluate yearly\nYES\nTest\n<5.7%\n<100mg/dl\n<140mg/dl\n 5.6-6.4%\n100-125mg/dl\n140-199mg/dl\n≥ 6.5%\n≥ 126mg/dl\n≥ 200mg/dl\nEncourage healthy\nlifestyle maintenance. \nRetest  at least every\n3 years.\nEncourage lifestyle \nmodification and \nretest every 6-12 \nmonths\nRetest with a \ndifferent test, and \nrefer for treatment \nif still positive.\nAdapted from the American Diabetic Association Standard of Medical Care in Diabetes.\nHaemoglobin A1C\nFasting plasma glycemia\nOral glucose tolerance test\nand Random glucose test\n*Known Risk Factors for Diabetes\n- PhysicaI inactivity\n- Family history of diabetes\n- High-risk race or ethnicity: African, \n  American, American Indian\n- Hypertension (≥ 140/90)\n- HDL-C <35 or Triglyceride > 250 mg/dL\n- History of gestational diabetes or gave \n  birth to a baby ≥4.5kg\n- History of heart disease\n- Conditions associated with insulin \n   resistance\n- Polycystic ovary syndrome\n-  Malnutrition \n \n• Evidence of Atherosclerosis \n• RA, SLE, Psoriasis \n• HIV infection on ARVs\n• EGFR < 60 mL/min/1.73m²\n• Erectile dysfunction \n• Screening children with a Family History of \n  Hypercholesterolemia or chylomicronemia.",
