    "text": "Section I: Periodic Health Examination\n7\nFigure 5: Protocol for counseling on tobacco and alcohol cessation using the 5 steps 5 A \napproach.\nASK \nADVISE  \nDo you use tobacco (in any form?\nReinforce the message that tobacco and alcohol increase the risk of heart disease and cancer, \ntherefore, not initiate. \n• Advise to quit in a clear and personalized manner. \n• Tobacco and alcohol use increases the risk of developing a heart attack, stroke, and cancer.\n• Quitting tobacco and alcohol is the most important thing that you can do to protect your heart and health -YOU HAVE TO QUIT NOW \nASSESS  \nASSIST  \nARRANGE   \nNo\nNo\nYes\nYes\nAre you willing to make a quit attempt now? \n• Set a quitting date. \n• Inform family and friends. \n• Ask for their support. \n• Remove cigarettes/tobacco in other forms and alcohol. \n• Remove objects/articles that prompt you to consume tobacco and alcohol.\n• Arrange follow-up visit at 1, 3, and 5 months.  \n• At follow-up visit \n• Congratulate success and reinforce. \n• If the patient has relapsed, consider more intensive follow-up and support \n  from family. \n \nFrequent follow-up and motivation to quit.\nProvide information on the health hazards of tobacco \nand alcohol to the individual. \nBenefits of quitting: \n• The body begins to heal almost immediately.\n• Quitting smoking immediately reduces\nRisks for cardiovascular disease and cancer including:\nCancers of the esophagus, larynx, kidney, pancreas, and cervix.\nBarriers to Quitting:  \n• Withdrawal symptoms and cravings\n• Stress\n• Fear of failure\n• Peer /social pressure\nPharmacological interventions to quit smoking.\nNicotine replacement therapy \nIt is taken for 12 weeks:\n• -0.5mg daily for 3 days\n• 0.5mg twice daily for the next 4 days\n• 1mg twice daily starting day 8 all the way to \n   the 12 weeks.  \n         Varenicline \n• Day 1–3: 0.5 mg once daily, in the morning \n• Day 4–7: 0.5 mg twice daily, in the morning and \n   the evening\n• Day 8 to end of treatment: 1 mg twice daily, in the \n  morning and the evening Start 1 week before \n  the day of smoking cessation. \n• Use for 3–6 months. \nBupropion \n• Dosing should begin at 150 mg/day, given every \n  morning for the first 3 days, followed by a dose.\n• Increase for most people to the recommended \n  dose of 300 mg/day.\n• The maximum recommended dose is 300 mg/day, \n   given as 150 mg twice daily.\n• Some persons do well on 150 mg once a day and \n  have fewer side effects.\n• An interval of at least 8 hours between successive \n  doses is advised.\n• The quit attempt should occur during the second \n  week of treatment \n2. Alcohol and Substance Use\nAlcohol is a psychoactive substance with dependence-producing properties whose harmful use causes a \nlarge number of diseases, social and economic burdens in societies. Alcohol remains a leading risk factor for \nmorbidity, disability, and mortality. Scientific evidence indicates alcohol is a component cause of more than \n200 diseases and injury conditions.",
