    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n23\nII.A.3  Acute Coronary Syndrome\nACS are caused by sudden reduction of blood supply to the heart. Each year 7 million people in the world are \ndiagnosed with ACS. Risk factors include hypertension, diabetes, smoking, sedentary lifestyle, and dyslipi­\ndaemia. Prompt diagnosis and reperfusion therapy reduces its associated high mortality and morbidity.\nFigure 11: Algorithm for Acute Coronary Syndromes (ACS) management at secondary care \nlevel.\nAcute Coronary Syndromes (ACS) management at secondary care level.\nSuspect ACS if a patient presents with the following at any facility.\nRetrosternal chest pain \nthat persists for >20 min.\nGive Po ASA 300mg start.\nST-Elevation MI\nNon-STE MI\nUnstable Angina\n• Dyspnoea\n• Diaphoresis\n• Nausea\n• Vomiting\n• Fatigue\n• Syncope\nObtain an ECG within \n             10 min.\nIt’s a complete coronary artery\nocclusion. Diagnose it if an \nST-segment elevation is ≥0.1mV \nin 2 limb leads or ≥0.2mV in two \ncontiguous precordial leads or a \nnew LBBB. \nStart Oral ASA 300mg stat, \nClopidogrel 600mg stat, Atorvastatin \n80mg stat. Refer the patient for \nprimary PCI within 120 min or not \nlater than 12 hours of first medical \ncontact. \nIt’s a non-complete coronary \nocclusion. Diagnose it when \nECG shows ST-segment \ndepression, T wave inversion or \ncombined + elevated troponins. \nStart Oral ASA 300mg stat, \nClopidogrel 600mg stat, Atorvastatin \n80mg stat, SC Enoxaparin 1mg/kg Q \n12 hours. Refer for PCI within 24-48 \nhours.\nRetrosternal chest pain on \nexertion or at rest + ST-segment \ndepression, TWI, or both. \n+/- cardiac troponins. \nStart Oral ASA 100mg OD, sub-\nlingual nitro-glycerine 400 mcg \nthat can be repeated after 5 min \nbut no more than 3 doses (1200 mcg). \nAdditional treatment includes \nbeta-blockers and statin. Refer for \ndiagnostic coronary angiography. \n1\n2\n4\n5\n3\nPlease note the following.\n        Angina pain is retrosternal, pressure-like sensation that lasts 5 to 30 min. It radiates to the neck, jaw, \n        back and left arm.\n        Atypical presentations with nausea, vomiting, dyspnoea or diaphoresis are more common in women, \n        diabetic and elderly patients.\n        A 12-lead ECG is a bedside procedure. It should be done by any registered nurse at the emergency in less\n        than 10 min after patient arrival and present it to the medical doctor as soon as possible to make the decision. \n        The ACS patient’s family or bystander should call the nearest ambulance service as soon as possible; all \n        ACS patients should be transported to the hospital by ambulance.  \n         When the health facility (health center, dispensary) does not have an electrocardiography machine, \n         suspected ACS patients should be immediately referred after receiving 300mg Aspirin orally (chewable).   \n6\n         Enoxaparin or Unfractioned Heparin shouldn’t be given prior to transfer if the invasive coronary \n         angiography/PCI is expected in less than 12 hours.",
