    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n25\nII.A.4  Stroke\nStroke is a clinical syndrome characterized by acute onset of focal cerebral loss of function lasting more \nthan 24 hours or leading to death and no apparent cause rather than vascular origin. Hypertension, diabetes, \ndyslipidemia, presence of known cardiac disease (A fib, CHF, CAD.), Some medications (OCP, anti-coagulants), \nunhealthy lifestyles (Smoking, illicit drug uses, Alcohol abuse), age, sex, race and genetics remain some risk \nfactors of Stroke. Its classified in both ischemic, hemorrhagic stroke and sub-arachnoid Hemorrhage.\nFigure 13: Algorithm for Stroke Diagnosis and Management\nConfirmed Ischemic Stroke  \nConsider other plausible diagnoses      \nIschemic changes\nNo Ischemic changes\nHemorrhage\nNo Hemorrhage\nIdentify signs and symptoms of stroke \nACT FAST transfer to Health center \n• Take vital signs, support ABCs, and  \n   give oxygen if needed.\n• Establish time of symptom onset.\n• Check glycaemia \n• Transfer to Hospital\n• Take vital signs, support ABCs, and \n   give oxygen if needed.\n• Obtain IV Access, Do FBC, U&E, PT &PTT \n   Lipid profile, HbA1c and Glycemia\n• Treat hypo and hyperglycemia \n  (according to protocol)\n• Obtain a 12 leads ECG \n• Emergent Brain CT/MRI\n• Assess stroke severity scales (NIH Stroke Scale\n  or Canadian Neurological Scale) see Neurologist\nDoes CT/MRI show Hemorrhage?\nConsult neurologist \n & neurosurgeon\nProbable or confirmed \nacute ischemic stroke        \nRepeat brain CT/MRI in first negative\nCT Brain\nHealth Center\n      Level\nDistrict H.\nProvincial H.\nReferral H.\nCommunity\nF\nONE SIDE OF THE\nFACE IS DROPPING\nFACE\nA\nARM OR LEG\nWEAKNESS\nARM\nS\nSPEECH\nDIFFICULTY\nSPEECH\nT\nTIME TO CALL\nFOR AMBULANCE\nIMMEDIATELY\nTIME\nSTROKE SYMPTOMS\n?\nSOS\nCALLING\nRemember, Recognize, and Act Fast",
