    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n27\nII.A.5  Rheumatic Heart Diseases\nRHD is defined as valvular damage caused by abnormal immune response to GAS infection in childhood. \nGlobally, it causes 300,000 deaths annually. Early diagnosis is key to reducing related morbidity and mortal­\nity. Valves affected are Mitral, Aortic, Tricuspid and rarely Pulmonic.\nFigure 14: Algorithm for Management of Rheumatic Heart Disease (RHD) at Secondary Care \nLevel.\nSuspect RHD if a patient presents with the following \nNew onset dyspnoea, \nfatigue or palpitations.\nTransfer to DH\nAt Health Center\nOrder CXR, FBC, RFTs, \n12-lead ECG. Confirm \ndiagnosis with \nEchocardiography.\n• Fast and irregular pulse\n• Hyperactive precordium\n• Loud murmur\n• Distended jugular veins\n• Ankle/leg edema.\nMitral Stenosis\nMitral Regurgitation\nAortic Insufficiency\nAortic Stenosis\nIf leaflets and sub-valvular \nthickening, commissural fusion, \ncalcification and accelerated \nforward flow on colour doppler. \nLeft atrium is usually dilated. \nIf leaflets and sub-valvular \nthickening, restricted leaflets \nmotion, accelerated backward \nflow on colour doppler; \nLV dilation +/- dysfunction. \nIf thickened cusps with rolled \nedges; accelerated backward \nflow on colour doppler; most \nof the time it is associated \nwith rheumatic mitral valve \nlesion (s). LV dilation +/- \ndysfunction. \nIf thickened cusps with rolled \nedges; accelerated forward \nflow on colour doppler; most of \nthe time it is associated with \nrheumatic mitral valve lesion (s). \nStart PO Atenolol 25mg if HR>90bpm \nand BP >90/60 mmHg, PO Penicillin V \n250mg BID; check for A Fib to start \nWarfarin 5mg OD. Therapeutic range \nINR (2-3). If in pulmonary oedema, \nadmit for IV Furosemide. Early referral \nfor Balloon Mitral Valvotomy (BMV) \nEF<60%: treat per HFrEF protocol, \nadd Penicillin V 250mg BID, urgent \nreferral to a Cardiologist.\nEF>60%: Low dose PO Furosemide, \nPenicillin V 250mg BID, non-urgent \nreferral to a Cardiologist. \nEF<60%: treat per HFrEF protocol, \nadd Penicillin V 250mg BID, urgent \nreferral to a Cardiologist.\nEF>60%: Low dose PO Furosemide, \nPenicillin V 250mg BID, non-urgent \nreferral to a Cardiologist. \nAortic Stenosis is a surgical condition. \nRefer patient to a cardiologist to \nquantify severity and plan surgery. \nAfterload reduction should be avoided \nunless AI or MR is associated. \n1\n2\n4\n5\n3\nPlease note the following.\nWomen should be educated and offered reproductive health service upon RHD diagnosis.\nPatients on Warfarin should have their INR checked regularly and kept within their therapeutic range.\nEstimate RVSP by TR jet CW if you can to inform management; don’t forget to check TV rheumatic changes.\nMixed Mitral or Aortic valve disease can be challenging in less experienced practitioner, consult for management.\nSecondary prophylaxis with Penicillin is recommended until 40 years of age.",
