    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n32\nII.B Pediatric Cardiology\nII.B.1 Congenital Heart Diseases\nStructural abnormalities of the heart or great vessels present at birth. They fall into 2 major groups: Acya­\nnotic and cyanotic. \nSummarized below is the algorithm with the initial evaluation and management of congenital heart diseases.\nCONGENITAL HEART DISEASES SCREENING\nMeasure 02 Sat in the right hand and any foot \nof all newborns between 24-36 hours of age.\n02 Sat ≥95% in the right hand or \nany foot and ≤3% difference \nbetween right hand and any \nfoot = Normal\n02 Sat between 90-94% in right \nhand and any foot or >3% \ndifference between right hand \nand any foot = Indefinite\n02 Sat < 90% in the right hand or \nany foot = Abnormal\nRepeat measurements in 1 hour\n02 Sat ≥95% in the right hand or \nany foot and ≤3% difference \nbetween right hand and any \nfoot = Normal\n02 Sat between 90-94% in right \nhand and any foot or >3% \ndifference between right hand \nand any foot = Indefinite\n02 Sat < 90% in the right hand or \nany foot = Abnormal\n02 Sat ≥95% in the right hand or \nany foot and ≤3% difference \nbetween right hand and any \nfoot = Normal\n02 Sat between 90-94% in right \nhand and any foot or >3% \ndifference between right hand \nand any foot = Indefinite\n02 Sat < 90% in the right hand or \nany foot = Abnormal\nRepeat measurements in 1 hour\nScreening Failed\nPediatric cardiologist consult\nScreening Passed\nPediatric cardiologist consult\nYes\n- Poor weight gain\n- Abnormal Heart Sounds (Murmur,Gallop,etc)\n- Diaphoresis\n- Recurrent chest infections\n- Cardiogenic shock\n- Respiratory distress\n- Hepatomegaly\nCentral cyanosis/Hypoxia\n- Cyanotic CHD\n- Pulmonary Diseases\n- Consider non-cardiac causes\n like sepsis, CNS disease, etc...\nHyperoxia test formal or\ninformal (15L of 02), 02 Sat\nincreases by 10%\nPulmonary Disease/ Non-cardiac\ncauses\nN.B: The hyperoxia test is not a\ndefinitive test, it does not\ncompletely exclude CHD\nAcyanotic CHD\nCyanotic CHD\n- Chest X-ray\n- EKG\n- Echocardiography\nYes\nNo\nNo",
