    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n33\nVolume overload:\nClinical manifestations\ndepend on the severity\nof the left-to-right shunt\nPressure overload:\nClinical manifestations \ndepend on the severity \nof the obstruction\nPulmonary stenosis\nAortic stenosis\nCoarctation of the aorta\nASD\nVSD/AVSD\nPDA/AOW\nIf critical, ductal \ndependent! Presents in \nthe first days of life in \nshock.\nIf non-critical: \nTachypnea, poor weight \ngain, poor feeding, \nejection murmur over \nthe pulmonary area.\nIf critical, ductal \ndependent! Presents in \nthe first days of life in \nshock.\nIf non-critical: \nTachypnea, poor weight \ngain, poor feeding, \nejection murmur over \naortic area.\nIf critical, ductal \ndependent! Presents in \nthe first days of life in \nshock.\nIf non-critical: HTN on \nupper limbs, radial artery \nto femoral artery pulse \ndelay, systolic murmur \nirradiating at the back.\nAsymptomatic, can \npresent with recurrent \nchest infections, and \npoor weight gain.\nPhysical findings: no \nrespiratory distress, \nejection murmur (most \nof the times absent) \npulmonary area, fixed \nsplit of S2. \nSymptoms appear first \nweeks of life: \nDiaphoresis, poor \nweight gain, poor \nfeeding, tachypnea, \nand tachycardia.\nPhysical findings: chest \nretraction, holosystolic \nmurmur at LLSB, \nhepatomegaly, Harrison \nsulcus.\nSymptoms appear first \nweeks of life: \nDiaphoresis,poor weight \ngain, poor feeding, \ntachypnea, tachycardia.\nPhysical findings:Chest \nretraction, continuous \nmurmur at the left \ninfraclavicular area, \nhepatomegaly.  \n1. General measures: Nutritional Support,\nprevention from URTI and IE\n2. Medical treatment if in heart failure: \nLasix 1-3mg/kg/day,\nAldactone 1-3mg/kg/day,\nCaptopril (with caution) 0.3-0.5 mg/kg/day\n3. Treat surgically or by catheterization\nthe underlying pathology\nAcyanotic CHD",
