    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n37\nII.B.3 Rheumatic Heart Diseases\nRheumatic Heart Disease (RHD) is an inflammatory damage of the heart valves, as a complication of acute \nrheumatic fever. The mitral valve is the most commonly involved valve, although any valve may be affected. \nSummarized below is the algorithm with the initial evaluation and management of RHD in children.\nFigure 18: Algorithm with the initial evaluation and management of RHD in children\nACUTE RHEUMATIC FEVER\nRHEUMATIC HEART DISEASE\n- 2-4 weeks after Group A Streptococcus\n- Diagnosis based on Revised Jones Criteria:\n*To prevent pain associated with Extencillin injection the drug must be mixed with low-dose \n  lidocaine hydrochloride 1% (3.5 – 5mls) solution\nMajor manifestations\n- Pancardlitis\n- Subcutaneous nodules\n- Sydenham chorea\n- Erythema marginatum\n- Arthritis (usually migratory polyarthritis)\nMinor manifestations\n- Fever (≥38°C)\n- Prolonged PR interval (on EKG)\n- ESR ≥60 mm in the first hour and/or \n  CRP ≥3.0 mg/dL.",
