    "id": 61,
    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n38\nII.B.4 Infective endocarditis\nInfective Endocarditis (IE) is an infection of heart valves or the endocardium. The infection can result in \ndamage of the heart valves and/or the endocardial tissue. Summarized below is the algorithm with the initial \nevaluation and management of IE in children.\nFigure 19: Algorithm with the initial evaluation and management of IE in children.\nDenotations\nCHD: Congenital Heart Disease; IE: Infective Endocarditis; RHD: Rheumatic Heart Disease.\nReferences\n1. O’Brien SE, Fulton DR, Edwards MS, Armsby C. Infective endocarditis in children. UpToDate. Published \nAugust 22, 2023. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/infective-endocarditis-in-children?search=infec­\ntive%20endocarditis&source=search_result&selectedTitle=1~150&usage_type=default&display_rank=1\nPatients at risk: children with CHD \n( cyanotic and acyanotic except ASD ), \nRHD , cardiac surgery within 6 months, \nchildren < 3 years , patients with \nprosthetic valves.\n                                         Modified Duke Criteria for diagnosis of IE (source : UptoDate) \n                                                                                   Major criteria\n \n- Positive blood cultures for organisms typical of IE: 2 separate blood cultures with typical organisms \nconsistent with IE, 2 or more positive blood cultures for blood samples drawn with a difference of >12 hours \n- For other organisms that are typically skin pathogens: 3 or ≥ 4 separate positive blood cultures \n( with at least a difference of 1 hour between first and last culture ) \n- 1 positive blood culture for Coxiella burnetii or IgG titer for Coxiella burnetii > 1 : 800 \n- Evidence of endocardial involvement on echocardiogram (vegetations, new valvular regurgitation, absess) \n                                                                                    Minor criteria \n- Fever ≥ 38.0 ° C \n- Predisposing cardiac disease or IV drug use \n- Vascular phenomena which are major arterial emboli , intracranial hemorrhage , septic pulmonary infarcts, \nmycotic aneurysm, conjunctival hemorrhage, Janeway lesions. \n- Immunologic phenomena which are glomerulonephritis, Osler nodes, Roth spots , rheumatoid factor \n- Positive culture but not meeting major criteria OR serologic evidence of active infection with pathogens \n  consistent of IE.\n \n* Diagnosis : Definite IE: 2 major OR 1 major plus 3 minor OR 5 minor criteria \n* Diagnosis : Possible IE: 1 major plus 1 minor OR 3 minor criteria\n                                                                 Management \n                                                      Antimicrobial treatment: \n- Based on culture and antibiogram \n- Duration: 4-6 weeks \n                                                                a . Prevention: \n- Oral hygiene and timely treatment of infections \n- Amoxicillin / Ampicillin for patients undergoing dental procedures\n \n                                                            b . If culture grows: \n- Staphylococcus aureus: cloxacilline 200mg/kg/day for methicillin susceptible strains, \n  Vancomycin 40mg/kg/day for MRSA. \n- Streptococcus: Ceftriaxone 100mg / kg / day \n- Enterococci: Ceftriaxone 100mg/kg/day and Ampicillin 200 to 300mg / kg per 24 hours \n- Gram negative: Ceftriaxone 100mg / kg / day\n \nc .",
