    "id": 63,
    "text": "Section Ii: Cardiology\n39\nII.B.5 Cardiogenic Shock\nCardiogenic shock results from pump failure to provide the systemic oxygen requirement. The patient is usu­\nally known for an underlying cardiac disease but may also be newly diagnosed with a cardiac disease.\nFigure 20: Algorithm with the initial evaluation and management of Cardiogenic shock in \nchildren.\nClinical presentation\n                              History:\n- Known case of heart disease\n- In neonates, consider ductal dependent \n  CHD\n- Poor weight gain, diaphoresis, dyspnea on\n  exertion, episodes of palpitations, poor \n  urine output\n                       Physical exam:\nTachycardia, cyanosis, respiratorydistress, \nCRT>8sec, cold extremities, weak distal \npulses, hypotension, murmur, gallop,\npulmonary edema, hepatomegaly, lethargy\nor altered level of consciousness\n                                Management: \n1. Immediately refer to a tertiary hospital for \nintensive care and pediatric, cardiologist review\n2. Semi-sitting position, 02 10-15L/min with \nmask and reservoir, ensure saturation >94%. If \napneic, plan for rapid intubation using Ketamine.\n3. Obtain IV access, give with caution Normal \nSaline 5ml-10ml/kg for 30 min, stop if worsening \nsigns of overload: increased respiratorydistress \n(Pulmonary edema), increased hepatomegaly\n4. Address hypothermia and anemia\n5. Vasoactive agents:\na. Dopamine (2-20mog/kg/min): first line in mild \nto moderate cardiogenic shock\nb. Dobutamine (2-20meg/kg/min) or milrinone \n(0.1-1mog/kg/min): if severe cardiogenic shock \nand the patient is not hypotensive.\nc. Epinephrine (0.01-1meg/kg/min) and \nnorepinephrine (0.01-1mcg/kg/min): if severe \ncardiogenic shock and hypotensive patient.\n6. Diuretics with caution: Furosemide continuous \nIV infusion of 0.05 to 0.4 mg/kg/hour.\n                     Clinical presentation\n                                History:\nPoor feeding, irritability, palpitations, chest’\ndiscomfort, fatigue\n                           Physical exam:\nTachycardia (infants: 220 to 280 bpm,\nchildren and adolescents: 180 to 240bpm), \ncyanosis, pallor, CRT>3sec, coldextremities, \nhepatomegaly, lethargy or altered level of \nconsciousness\nManagement:\n1. Start immediately the process of referring to a \ntertiary hospital forintensive care and pediatric \ncardiologist review\n2. Do EKG if available and consider SVT, \nventricular dysrhythmias, AFib, Atrial flutter, etc.\n3. Hold IV fluids\n4. Consider vagal maneuver/cardioversion/\nantiarrhythmic medications (Beta-blockers: \npropranolol 0.5mg/kg/dose, adenosine, Digoxin).\nConsider other causes of shock:\nHypovolemia, sepsis, anaphylaxis\nCARDIOGENIC SHOCK\nDenotations\nAFib: Atrial fibrillation, CHD: Congenital Heart Disease; SVT: Supraventricular Tachycardia.\nReferences\n1. Wooldridge G, Hitayezu J, Venkatasubbu P. Paediatric cardiogenic shock. Published online 2021. \ndoi:10.1029/WFSA-D-19-00022",
