    "text": "Section Iii: Diabetes Mellitus\n41\n3. Type 2 Diabetes pharmacological treatment \nFigure 22: Algorithm for type 2 diabetes pharmacological treatment.\n  \nAt diagnosis, HbA1c (Available) management includes lifestyle changes \n(diet, exercise, weight loss, stop smoking) + Drugs (individualize patients)\nHbA1c less 9%(<212mg/dl)  \nHbA1c ≥9% (<212mg/dl)\nconsider dual therapy \nHbA1c ≥10% or =300 mg/dl \nmarkedly symptomatic \nconsider adding insulin \nInitiate Metformin 500mg \ndaily for 5 days then twice \na day if good tolerability. \nMaximum dose:1g twice\nHbA1c at a target at 3 months, \nif there is no target with good \nadherence and max dose \nconsider dual therapy\nMetformin + (Sulfonylureas: \nGliclazide as first choice, \nGlimepiride as a second choice, \nGlibenclamide as a third choice)\nif HbA1c is not at target at 3 months\nMetformin + two additional \ndrugs (Sulphonurea or DPP4 \ninhibitors or SGLT 2 inhibitors\nHbA1c at target at 3 mo, if no \ntarget with good adherence/\nmax dose  consider more than \n3 therapy \nHbA1c at target at 3 mo, if no \ntarget with good adherence/\nmax dose  consider combination \nof injectable \n(NPH/LONG ACTING INSULIN )\n• The best choice to add on \nmetformin is SUs, (DPP4 inhibitors, SGLT2\n• Consider ABCD (Age, BMI, Complications, \nand Duration of the disease when choosing \nother drugs to add. \n4. Indications of insulin therapy Absolute indications\n                  \n-  All Types 1 DM\n- Type2  DM with maximum dose, more  than 3 oral drugs and not in target \n- Transient insulin therapy may be necessary in case of: \n    • Type 2 Diabetes with acute complications\n    • Perioperative period, \n    • Acute infection,\n    • Pregnancy…\n    • Type 1 Diabetes \n    • Type 2 Diabetes which does not respond to maximum dose of oral anti-diabetic agents and HbA1C>9% Secondary\nInsulin dosing: 0.5Ui/kg/h (total daily dose)\n• 2/3 morning (before breakfast), 1/3 evening (before dinner) for Insulin Lente\n• 70%: NPH or other long-acting insulin \n• 30%: Regular insulin\n5. Outpatient Regimens\nTable 5: Treatment options in management of Diabetes in outpatient\nBreakfast\nLunch\nDinner\nBedtime\nAdvantages\nDisadvantages\nIntermediate +short acting\n( e.g.: NPH)\n-\nIntermediate \n+short acting -\n-\nLess injection/ day\nRequire usual physical \nactivities and same \ncalories /day\nShort acting ± intermediate \ninsulin\n( e.g. Regular )\nShort acting \ninsulin\nIntermediate \n+short acting\nIntermediate \ninsulin\n- Free Life style \n-No need of snacks \nGood glycemic \ncontrol\nMany injections/ day\nOral agents\n± oral agent\nIntermediate \ninsulin\nLess injections\nPostprandial BG not well \ncontrolled",
