    "text": "Section Iii: Diabetes Mellitus\n47\nIII.C Management of Diabetes in pregnancy  \nGestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) is any degree of\nonset or first recognized during pregnancy impaired glucose tolerance \n• Universal screening (screening every pregnant woman) is recommended by many guidelines.\n• Previous GDM\n• Maternal age > 35 years\n• Family history of diabetes (first-degree relative with diabetes)\n• Obesity (BMI > 30 kg/m²)\n• Previous macrosomia (birthweight > 4500g)\n• Polycystic Ovary Syndrome\n• Iatrogenic: glucocorticoids and antipsychotic medication\n• Hypertension  \n GDM, anytime in pregnancy:\n    • Fasting plasma glucose 5.1–6.9 mmol/L (92–125 mg/dL)\n    • 1-hour plasma glucose 10.0 mmol/L (180 mg/dL) following a 75g oral \n      glucose load 2-hour plasma glucose 8.5–11.0 mmol/L (153–199 mg/dL) \n      following a 75g oral glucose load  \n• Exercise 30-60 min moderate intensity \n• Diet:  regular meal plan; 3 moderate-sized meals, \n  4 snacks, \n• Low sugar \n• Insulin if lifestyle DOESN’T work 0.7-1 unit/kg \n• Metformin can be considered if no concerns with \n   inadequate fetal growth. Start 500 mg with dinner \n   and increase to 500 mg bd, max not beyond 2500. \n• Glyburide is an alternative \n• Fasting and pre-prandial blood glucose \n  concentration: <95 mg/dL (5.3 mmol/L)\n• One-hour postprandial blood glucose \n  concentration: <140 mg/dL (7.8 mmol/L)\n• Two-hour postprandial glucose concentration: \n  <120 mg/dL (6.7 mmol/L)\nCheck HbA1c every 4-6 weeks, Goal below 6.5%\nLifestyle modification \nPharmacotherapy \nGlycemic goal \nDiabetes mellitus in pregnancy\n   • Fasting plasma glucose 7.0 mmol/L (126 mg/dL)\n   • 2-hour plasma glucose 11.1 mmol/L (200 mg/dL) following a 75g oral \n     glucose load\n   • Random plasma glucose 11.1 mmol/L (200 mg/dL) in the presence of \n     diabetes symptom \nNo role of HbA1c in the diagnosis of GDM \n• Prediabetes or Impaired glucose tolerance \n    o HbA1C ≥ 5.7%, impaired glucose tolerance or impaired fasting glucose\n    o HbA1C >6.5%, diagnosis of preexisting diabetes\nNote: symptoms may be unspecific  \nGlucose values fall into diagnostics ranges of either Impaired glucose \ntolerance (IGT) or Diabetes (DM)\n1. Definition\n2. Screening\n3. Diagnosis Criteria (WHO)\n 4.",
