    "text": "Section Iii: Diabetes Mellitus\n52\nFigure 26: Algorithm for management of DKA and HHS\nTransfer\nClinical suspicion: polyuria, polydipsia, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, fruit smell, \nrapid and deep breathing, mental status change, hyperglycemia>250mg/dl, positive urine ketones.\nHealth Center:\n• Vital signs, IV access\n• IV NaCl 1 liter bolus then \n  500 mls continuous then\n• Immediate transfer to DH\n• If using continuous IV: 0.1 IU/kg \n  bolus then hourly.\n• If continuous IV not available: 10 \n  IU regular insulin 10IU IV then \n  0.1IU/kg hourly SC.\n• Continue until negative ketonuria\n• If BG does not    by 50-70 mg/dL \n  within 1 hour, increase the rate by \n  50%.\n• When BG < 250mg/dl, decrease by \n  50% of the current rate.\n• Maintain BG 150-200mg/dl until \n  DKA and HHS resolution.\n• If hemodynamically unstable, \n  give 1 L over 30 minutes. \n  Repeat this until stable\n• If stable, give 1L over 1hour\n• Maintenance:250-500ml/hourly \n  for the first 4 hours and monitor \n  vital signs, free water deficit, urine \n  output.\nChange fluids to 5%DNS (250-250) \nwhen BG is <250mg/dl.\nDistrict or Provincial hospital:\n• Vital signs, volume status (  skin turgor, dry mucosa,\n  tachycardia, hypotension), mental status change\n• Serum blood glucose, urine ketones\n• Urea, creatinine, Na, K, Cl, ABG\n• Evaluate for precipitating causes: FBC, urinalysis/culture,\n  blood cultures, CXR, EKG, cardiac enzymes\nDiabetic Ketoacidosis \n• Hyperglycemia: BG>250 <500 mg/dL \n• Euglycemia <250mg/dl (pregnancy, SGLT2 use)\n• Ketonuria or ketonemia: highly positive\n• Acidosis pH: <7.3, low HCO3- :<10 ≤ 15 mEq/L\n• Anion gap: >12 (see formula)\nPotassium chloride\n• >5.2 mEq/L:monitor \n• 3.3-5.2mEq/L:add 20 mEq/L \n  2hourly\n• <3.3 mEq/L:add 30 mEq/L to \n   IVF 4 hourly\n• Keep serum K in the range 4 to \n  5 mEq/L\n• <3.3 mEq/L: delay insulin until \n  KCl initiated.",
