    "text": "Section Iii: Diabetes Mellitus\n59\nIf the patient is unconscious or convulsing and unable to take anything by mouth, lie them on their side and \nkeep their airway clear – i.e., the ABC of resuscitation – airway, breathing, circulation.\nSevere hypoglycemia with loss of consciousness ± convulsions (or if the child is vomiting)\n- In the ambulatory setting SC or IM glucagon should be given (1 mg for children > 25kg and 0.5 mg for chil­\ndren < 25kg.\n- In a hospital setting, IV glucose (10% dextrose, 2ml/kg) can be administered and should be given carefully \nand slowly over several minutes.  \nFigure 28: Algorithm for management of hypoglycemia in children\n\t\nIII.E.3.1 Hyperglycemia in a child who is not sick.\nIn the presence of any of these:\n   • Very young children with diabetes, who may become dehydrated more \n      rapidly than older children or adolescents.\n   • Nausea or vomiting that prevents the child from drinking.\n   • Parent’s inability to check blood glucose at home\n   • If supportive care cannot be ensured at home\n   • If the acute illness is severe\n   • If there is persistent ketonuria.\nHyperglycaemia can be treated with small doses of extra rapid-acting insulin. \nGive 10% of the child’s usual total meal dose, rounded off to the nearest half or \nfull unit. Adequate fluid intake is paramount. Elevated blood glucose results \nwith moderate or large amounts of ketones. Give: 10-20% of a total daily dose \nof insulin as rapid-acting insulin repeated every 2-4 hours. \nWhen vomiting occurs in a child with diabetes, it should always be considered \na sign of insulin deficiency (impending ketoacidosis) until proven otherwise. \nStrenuous exercise should be avoided.   \nCriteria for admission\nConsider transferring to an appropriate setting (well-equipped and available skill) if the child is not showing \nimprovement.\n             Hypoglycemia \nBlood glucose level < 4mmol/L\nDO NOT LEAVE CHILD \n        UNATTENDED\nCheck blood glucose level to \n        confirm < 4mmol/L\n                                 Step 1 \nGive 10-20g of fast-acting carbohydrate \n(amount dependent on age and size of child)\n                      Step 3 \nTreat with 10-20g slow-acting \ncarbohydrate.\nRepeat Step 1\n                                 Step 2 \nCheck blood glucose level after 10 minutes.\nIs the blood glucose level > 4mmol/L?\nSigns and symptoms can include: \nPallor, shakiness, headache, sweating, hunger, \ndizziness, irritability, mood change, confusion, \ncrying, weakness, and blurred vision.\nYES\nNO",
