    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n66\nMineral bone disorder management\nA systemic disorder of mineral and bone metabolism due to CKD manifested by either one or a combination \nof the following:\n1. Abnormalities of calcium, phosphorus, Parathyroid Hormone (PTH), or vitamin D metabolism. \n2. Abnormalities in bone turnover, mineralization, volume linear growth, strength, vascular or other soft-tis­\nsue calcification. \n \nFigure 35: Algorithm for Management of bone mineral disorder\nCKD G3a.\nCalcium, phosphate, \nPTH, and alkaline \nphosphatase\nSerum calcium \nand phosphate PTH \nevery 6–12 months. \nSerum calcium\nand phosphate, \nevery 3–6 months; \nand for PTH, every \n6–12 months.\nSerum calcium\nand phosphate, \nevery 1–3 months; \nand for PTH, every \n3–6 months\nAlkaline phosphatase \nactivity, every 12\nmonths, or more \nfrequently in the \npresence of elevated \nPTH.  \nCKD G3a–G3b\nCKD G4D\nCKD G5\nCKD G4–G5D\nAbnormal  PTH levels\nCKD G3a-G5\nCKD G3a–G5 \nnot on dialysis\nCKD G5D\n CKD G5D requiring \nPTH-lowering therapy\n CKD G5D requiring \nPTH-lowering therapy\nEvaluate for \nmodifiable factors, \nhyperphosphatemia, \nhypocalcemia, high \nphosphate intake, and \nvitamin D deficiency\nNo routine use of \ncalcitriol and vitamin \nD analogs reserve the \nuse of calcitriol and \nvitamin D analogs for \npatients with CKD \nG4–G5 with severe \nand progressive \nhyperparathyroidism. \nKeep iPTH levels in \nthe range of \napproximately 2 to 9 \ntimes the upper \nnormal limit for the \nassay.\nCalcimimetics, \ncalcitriol, or vitamin D \nanalogs, or a \ncombination of \ncalcimimetics with \ncalcitriol or vitamin D \nanalogs\nSevere hyperpara-\nthyroidism (HPT) \nwho fail to respond to \nmedical or pharma-\ncologicaltherapy: \nparathyroidectomy.\nPhosphate: limit daily phosphate intake, \nPhosphate binders examples of food and drugs",
