    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n70\nTable 12. Classification of CKD in children\nGFR Calculation \nGFR (ml / min/ 1.73m²) calculation by Schwartz formula = k X Ht (cm) /Pcr (µmol/L) \nGFR = 36.5 x height / serum creat in mmol\nCKD Classification according to GFR\nStage\nGFR \nFeatures\n1\n≥90\nUsually no symptoms, \n2\n60-89\nUsually, no symptoms may develop biochemical imbalances\n3\n30-59\nBiochemical abnormalities present, anemia, poor growth\n4\n15-29\nMore severe symptoms\n5\n<15\nESRD, Renal replacement therapy\n5. Investigation and Diagnosis\nImaging  \n1.Renal ultrasound \nOther Studies in selected cases \n1)Voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG) for suspicion of CAKUT \n   (such as PUV’s, VUR) \n2) MRI or CT-scan when better resolution and visualization than that provided \n     by ultrasound is needed. \n3) A vascular imaging procedure: \n      a)Doppler sonography of the renal arteries. \n      b) Magnetic resonance angiography (MRA).\n4) Renal biopsy (usually indicated in glomerular diseases)\nLaboratory investigation \n• FBC \n• Urinalysis, a 24-hour urine collection for protein excretion.\n• Serum creatinine (estimation of GFR)\n• Serum and urinary protein  \n• Electrolytes and CMP (Na+, Cl-, K+, Ca2+, Mg, P04) \n6. Approach to CKD Management\nFigure 37: Algorithm for CKD Management in children\n• Treat blood borne \n  infections. \n• Immunizations\n• Iron/folic acid \n  supplements \n• rHuEpo treatment.\nIdentify bone disorder \ncontrol P, Ca2+, PTH levels, \ncorrect acidosis & NA \nDepletion.\nAdequate nutrition, \nVit supplements, correct \nacidosis & Na depletion, \nprevent renal bone disease \nrhGH treatment.\nPhysiotherapy, treat learning \ndisabilities, treat speech/\nhealing impairments \n& social familial support\nControl HTN, Prevent \nfluid overload, treat \nhyperlipidemia. \n             Medications \n• ACEI ( proteinuria /HTN)\n  > Captoptil: 0.01–0.5 \n    mg/kg/dose PO Q8–12h \n  > Enalapril: 0.1–0.6 \n     mg/kg/24 h PO.",
