    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n72\nIV.B.2 Urinary tract infection (UTI) and urinary tract abnormalities\n1. Introduction\nThe majority of children and adolescents with chronic kidney disease have underlying kidney and urinary \ntract abnormalities.  Most of these children present first with signs of UTI. Hence, timely investigations and \nproper management of children with UTI are paramount to prevent or delay CKD in children.\nFigure 38: Algorithm for Urinary tract infection clinical presentation and management\n2. Management of recurrent UTI and atypical UTI \nIn our clinical context, it is recommended to do an abdominal ultrasound to exclude congenital abnormalities \nand renal scarring in case of every documented UTI. \nDilated/Obstructed Urinary Tract on US\nInfants\nOlder children\nDo VCUG\nIf thick-walled bladder \nconsiders PUV\nVUR\nUTI/Female\nMild dilatation, \nNo UTI\nModerate & \nsevere \ndilatation\nRefer to Urologist \nObstructed\nSuprapubic/urethral \ncatheter drainage\nUrologist Cystoureth-\nroscopy & valve \nfulguration/ablation\nYes\nNo\nVCUG\nVUR\nYes\nNo\nProphylactic ATBs\nUrologist/Pediatrician, \n3-6 month\nProphylactic ATBs\nRefer to Urologist \nDMSA renal scan\nRefer to Urologist \nObstructed\nNo\nYes\nRepeat U/S, \n3-6 months\nRepeat U/S, \n3-6 months\nIf severe, \ndrainage\nIf severe, \ndrainage\nConsider \nsurgical relief\nConsider \nsurgical relief\nNo\nYes\n        Symptoms /signs \n• Bloody urine (hematuria)\n• Cloudy/foul-smelling urine\n• Pain on micturition \n• Frequency\n• Lower abdominal pain\n• Secondary enuresis\n• Vomiting, diarrhea\n• History of recurrent UTI \n• Non-specific symptoms \n   in infants \n• Lower quadrant pain \n• Palpable bladder \nSUSPECTED UTI \n                        Investigations \nUrinalysis: dipstic /Leucocytes + Then do \nurine culture in a sterile manner possible\n \nFBC, CRP, UE, BLOOD CULTURE IF \nSERIOUSLY UNWELL \n• Growth of a single organism at > 108 \n  CFU/liter (> 105 CFU/ml) from any collection \n  method suggests infection.\n• Growth of a single organism at lower counts \n  of 106-8 CFU/liter (> 103-5 CFU/ml) from the \n  urinary catheter, clean catch, or MSU may \n  indicate early infection.\n• Growth of any amount from SPA suggests \n  infection.\nUTI Confirmed \n                                                                     TREATMENT \n1. UNWELL–IV ANTIBIOTIC cefixime/amoxycillin-clavulanic for 3-7 days/Nitrofurantoin \n2. Well and tolerating oral, give oral antibiotic (cefixime/amoxicillin-clavulanic)\n3. Total duration of antibiotic: 3 days for cystitis (UTI without systemic signs) 7 days for \n     pyelonephritis",
