    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n76\nIV.B.4 Nephrotic Syndrome in Children\n1. Definition \n• Nephrotic syndrome is a clinical syndrome defined by: \n> Nephrotic range proteinuria – Nephrotic range proteinuria is usually defined as >50 mg/kg/day    or 40 \nmg/hr/m² in a 24-hour urine collection or proteinuria of 3 to 4+ by dipstick or Urine protein to Creatinine ratio \n(UPC) >2 g/l creatinine (>0.2 g/mmol)\n> Hypoalbuminemia – The plasma albumin level is typically less than 2.5 g/dL (25 g/L)). \n• Most children with nephrotic syndrome respond well to adequate dosage of glucocorticosteroid therapy If \npoorly treated, nephrotic syndrome carries high morbidity and may progress to CKD. \n2. Clinical sign and symptoms \n• Swelling, particularly in the face and extremities.\n• Foamy urine.\n• Fatigue and weakness.\n• Elevated cholesterol levels.\n• Risk of blood clots and related complications.\n• Abdominal pain or discomfort.\n• Decreased urine output.\n• Edema symptoms (ie. significant ascites, pleural effusions \nClinical symptoms  \nClinical signs  \nSigns of fluid overload \n• Documentation of weight gain \n• Nephrotic range proteinuria\n• Hypoalbuminemia\n• Edema\n• ± Hyperlipidemia (not always required for diagnosis)\n• Foamy or frothy urine due to proteinuria.\nIntravascular volume depletion\n• Tachycardia\n• Elevated creatinine,\n• Edema \n• Risk of blood clots (thrombosis).\n• Decreased urine output (oliguria\nOther signs\n• Increased susceptibility to infections.\n• Hypertension \n• Hematuria \n3. Investigation and Diagnosis \nThe diagnosis of nephrotic syndrome is confirmed by the presence of both nephrotic range proteinuria and \nhypoalbuminemia:\n• Urine dipsticks\n• Urinalysis with microscopy\n• 24-hour urine protein\n• Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) and creatinine\n• Full blood count\n• Complement studies (C3, C4)\n• Serum lipids\n• Serum electrolytes\n• Suspected systemic lupus erythematosus:  antinuclear antibody (ANA) level \n  and anti-ds DNA antibody.\n• Kidney Biopsy if fulfilling criteria.  \n1.Primary Nephrotic Syndromes\n   • Minimal Change Disease (MCD)\n   • Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis (FSGS)\n   • Membranous Nephropathy\n   • Membranoproliferative Glomerulonephritis (MPGN)\n2. Secondary Causes\n   • Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)\n   • Diabetes Mellitus (Diabetic nephropathy)\n   • Amyloidosis\n   • Infections: such as HIV and hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and Syphilis.\n   • Drug-Induced Nephropathy\n3. Genetic and Congenital Disorders: \n   • Alport Syndrome.\n   • Congenital Nephrotic Syndrome\n4. Systemic Diseases\n   • Multiple Myeloma.\n   • Systemic Vasculitis.\n   • Sarcoidosis.\n5. Inflammatory and Infectious Causes\n   • IgA Nephropathy (Berger's Disease\n   • Post-Infectious Glomerulonephritis\n6.",
