    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n79\nAcute Complications of nephrotic syndrome \nConsider the most serious complications of nephrotic syndrome.\n   • Thromboembolism: suspect if severe headache, limb swelling \n   • Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis: suspect if severe abdominal pain and fever \n   • Infection: If there are concerns (i.e., Fever) culture and start empiric antibiotics covering for pneumococcus (Streptococcus pneumonia) and gram-negative \n     bacteria (Predominantly Escherichia coli)\n4.4. Second-line agents for frequently relapsing /glucocorticoid–dependent idiopathic ne­\nphrotic syndrome\nSecond-line agents for frequently relapsing/\nglucocorticoid-dependent idiopathic nephrotic \nsyndrome\nGlucocorticoid dependent\nFrequent relapses\nTreatment options \nStop if no relapse \nStop if no relapse \nLevamisol 2.5 mg/kg\nQ48H at least 12 months\nIneffective/breakthrough\nrelapses\nCalcineurin inhibitor\nTacrolimus 0.1−0.2/kg/day or\nCSA 5−7 mg/kg/day\nat least 12 months\nIneffective/breakthrough/\nAdverse effects \n(GI/hematological)\nMycophenolate 600 (–1200) \nmg/m²/day (or MPA-Na)a\nat least 12 months\nBreakthrough relapses,\nCNI toxicity\nRituximab Q4−6 months\nTaper and stop other\nimmunosuppressants\nas tolerated",
