    "text": "Section Iv: Nephrology\n80\n4.5. Summary Symptomatic approach\n5. Conclusion\n• Nephrotic syndrome caries poor prognosis if not treated timely and adequately. \n• Quantification of proteinuria should be done whenever possible. \n• Children who do not respond to initial 6 weeks of appropriate dose of steroid or who present with atypical \nfeatures, should be referred for Kidney biopsy. \n• Fluid (+/- 75% maintenance) and salt restriction\n• Consideration of 25% albumin infusion if pre-renal \n  or presence of anasarca\n• FeNa may be helpful to determine the response to\n  diuretics alone or albumin and diuretic.\n• Furosemide if fluid overload IV start 1 to 2 \n  mg/kg/dose,2nd dose 6 hours later Max 6mg/kg\n• Calcium channel blockers Amlodipine oral 0.05 to \n  0.3 mg/kg/dose OD Max 0.6 mg/kg/dose or 10 mg \n• IV Labetalol 0.2 to 1 mg/kg/dose if severe HTN \n   N.B Avoid ACEi & ARBs in AKI\nSigns of volume overload (hypertension, edema) \nor intravascular volume depletion (ie. Tachycardia, \nelevated creatinine, edema), \nPatient hypertensive\nAcute Symptomatic Management\n                                  Considerations for admission\n• Volume overload or depletion requiring IV management.\n• Severe, symptomatic edema (i.e., significant ascites, pleural effusions)\n• Symptomatic hypertension.\n• Renal dysfunction\n• Concerns of acute complications (discussed above)\n                                    Further management\n• If frequently relapsing or dependent, consider low-dose \n  maintenance steroids or second-line immunosuppressive \n  medications \n• If steroid-resistant, plan for kidney biopsy\n• Careful search for complications and prompt management is \n  important. \n• Long-term follow-up is crucial.  \nINDICATION FOR KIDNEY BIOPSY \nYou should consider biopsy if:\n• The patient is between 3 months and 12 months of age or over 12 years old.\n• There is gross hematuria (not related to renal vein thrombosis)\n• They are hypertensive.\n• They have abnormal kidney function (e.g., low eGFR) not pre-renal in nature.\n• C3 is low.\n• There is evidence of systemic disease (e.g., arthritis or rashes)\n• They are steroid-resistant defined by the persistence of proteinuria after 4 weeks of adequate dosage steroid \n  therapy.",
