While arranging give SABA, \n  ipratropium bromide, oxygen, \n  and systemic corticosteroid.\n• After ICU discharge refer for \n  follow-up\n                         Follow up.\n• Reliever: reduce as needed\n• Controller: continue higher dose for \n  short term (1-2 weeks) or long term \n  (3 months), depending on background \n  to exacerbation. \n• Risk factors: check and correct \n  modifiable risk factors that may have \n  contributed to exacerbation, including \n  inhaler technique and adherence. \n• Action plan: is it understood? Was it \n  used appropriately? Does it need \n  modification?\n                                                                      Transfer to respiratory specialist\n• Difficult to treat asthma is asthma that is uncontrolled despite prescribing of medium or high dose ICS-LABA or \n  that requires high dose ICS-LABA to maintain good symptom control and reduce exacerbations.\n• This may be due to uncontrolled environmental factors or comorbidities.\n• Severe asthma is uncontrolled asthma despite adherence with optimized high-dose ICS-LABA and treatment of \n  contributory factors or worsening when high-dose treatment is decreased.",
