    "id": 133,
    "text": "Section V: Chronic Respiratory Diseases\n91\nV.B.2 Chronic asthma in children\nChronic asthma in children is a long-term respiratory condition marked by recurring airway inflammation and \nnarrowing. It leads to symptoms like wheezing, coughing, and shortness of breath. Proper management and \na personalized action plan are essential to control symptoms and improve a child's quality of life.\nConfirmation of \ndiagnosis\nSymptom control \nmodifiable risk factors\nInhaler technique\n & adherence\nSymptoms most \ndays, waking at night \n≥1 a week\nMedium or high dose ICS\nLABA (child ≥4 years) plus \nas needed SABA. Refer \nfor expert advice.\nMedium dose ICS, plus \nas-needed SABA\nMedium dose ICS-LABA  \nplus as-needed SABA, or \nlow dose MART. Refer \nfor expert advice\nLow dose ICS-Formoterol \nmaintenance and reliever \n(MART). Refer for expert\nadvice\nMedium/high dose ICS-\nLABA  plus as-needed \nSABA (or ICS-SABA). \nRefer for expert advice\nLow dose ICS-Formoterol \nmaintenance and reliever \n(MART)\nLow dose ICS-LABA plus \nas-needed SABA \n(or ICS-SABA)\nAs needed-only low dose \nICS - Formoterol\nDaily low dose ICS +\nas-needed SABA \n(or ICS-SABA)\nAs needed-only low dose \nICS - Formoterol\nTake low dose ICS \nwhenever SABA taken\nDistrict hospital\nLow dose ICS-LABA  or \nmedium dose ICS, plus \nas-needed SABA, or very \nlow dose MART\nDaily low dose ICS + \nas-needed SABA\nTake ICS whenever SABA \ntaken\nDaily low dose ICS plus \nas-needed SABA\nAs-needed inhaled SABA\nSymptoms twice a \nmonth or more?\nSymptoms most days, \nwaking at night ≥ 1 a \nweek and low lung \nfunction\nChild and parent/\ncaregiver preferences \nand goals\nComorbidities\nTertiary/referral hospital\nYes\nYes\nNo\nNo\nNo\nYes\nStep 4\nStep 3\nStep 2\nStep 1\nAged ≥12 years \nAged 6-11 years  \nAged < 6 years  \nSTART WITH:   \nIF:   \nFIRST ASSESS:   \nTRACK 1 (preferred): \nTRACK 2:  \nOCS (Oral corticosteroids): e.g.: Prednisolone\nMART: e.g.: Beclomethasone-Formoterol / Budesonide-Formoterol \nLow, medium, and high daily metered doses of inhaled corticosteroids (alone or with LABA)\nThis is not a table of equivalence, but instead, suggested total daily doses for ‘low’, ‘medium’, and ‘high’ \ndose ICS options for adolescents ≥ 12 years and children 6–11 years, based on product information. Few \ndata are available for comparative potency, and this table does NOT imply potency equivalence. Doses may \ndiffer depending on local products, regulatory labeling, and clinical guidelines or, for one product, with the \naddition of a LAMA to an ICS-LABA. For f children aged 5 years and younger, data on comparative potency are \nnot readily available, particularly for children, and this table does NOT imply potency equivalence. The doses \nlisted here are the lowest approved doses for which safety and effectiveness have been adequately studied \nin this age group.\nLow-dose ICS provides most of the clinical benefits of ICS for most patients with asthma.",
