    "text": "Section Vi: Pain Management And Palliative Care\n94\nManagement of Pain\nThe management of pain in adults is referred from WHO analgesic ladder. \n Figure 45: Stepwise management of pain   \nCategory of Drugs\nNon-opioids          Ibuprofen or other NSAID, paracetamol (acetaminophen), or aspirin\nWeak opioids        Codeine, tramadol, or low-dose morphine\nStrong opioids      Morphine, Fentanyl, Oxycodone, Hydromorphone, Buprenorphine\nAdjuvants              Antidepressant, Anticonvulsant, Antispasmodic, Muscle relaxant, Bisphosphonate, or Corticosteroid.\n*\tCombining an opioid and non-opioid is effective, but do not combine drugs of the same class. \n*\tTime doses based on drug half-life (“dose by the clock”); do not wait for pain to recur.\n     Step 1\nNon-Opioid\n+/- Adjuvant\n                    Step 2\nWeak opioid for moderate pain\n            +/- Non-opioid\n            +/- Adjuvant\n                  Step 3\nStrong opioid for severe pain\n             +/- Non-opioid\n             +/- Adjuvant\nStep up if pain persists or increases\nStep down if pain decreases\nMild (0–3)\n Moderate (4–6)\n Severe (7-10)\nCategory\nDrug and dosage\nCaution and contraindications\nParacetamol: Give 500-1g 6-8 hourly\nIbuprofene: Give 400mg 6-8 hourly\nDiclofenac: Give 50mg 8-12 hourly\n• Hepatotoxicity\n• Maximum dose of 4g per day\n• Give with food.\n• Maximum dose 1.2g \n• Avoid asthma and peptic ulcer.\n• Lower dose if liver impairment.\n• Give with food and avoid in asthma \n  patients and peptic ulcer.\n• Maximum dose 150mg\nNon-opioid\nTramadol: Give 50-100mg 4-6 hourly \nCodeine: Give 30-60mg 4 hourly\nCaution with epileptic patients\n• Maximum dosage 240mg daily\n• Give laxatives to avoid constipation \n   unless the patient has diarrhea.\n• Low-dose morphine is given if the \n  maximum dose cannot work.\nWeak Opioid\n• Morphine: Start with 2.5-20mg q4h for \n  immediate release\n   > Give 8-24 hourly for slow release.\n   > 5% - 20% daily dose is used to \n      calculate the starting dose to treat \n      breakthrough pain\n• No ceiling dose of morphine \n  (give gradually until pain is controlled)\n• Pethidine can be used for acute pain \n  (NOT for chronic pain)\nStrong Opioid\nLess commonly used strong opioids in our settings: Fentanyl, Oxycodone, Hydromorphone, Methadone",
