    "id": 140,
    "text": "Section Vi: Pain Management And Palliative Care\n96\nVI.B Adult Palliative Care \nIntroduction\nPalliative care is the prevention and relief of suffering of any kind including physical, psychological, social, or \nspiritual experienced by adults and children living with serious health problems.\nIt is a people-centered accompanying of patients and their families throughout the illness course, including \nduring treatment and at the end of life, that optimizes quality of life and maximizes dignity. Palliative care \nneeds to be holistic and initiated at the time of diagnosis and continue after death (Bereavement care)\n Figure 46: Palliative care in the trajectory of the patient's illness\n  \n                 \nSome cases of palliative care improve towards the survivorship stage.\nFigure 47: Stages in palliative adapted from Hawley P.J pain symptom management 2014         \nHolistic approach in palliative care\nThe holistic approach is one that regards the patients as a whole person recognizing them as comprising \npsychological, social, spiritual and physical aspect.\nTherapies to modify disease \nCurative, restorative intent\nPresentation \n- Diagnosis\nLife closure\nActively dying\nBereavement care\nDeath\nTherapies to relieve suffering \nand/or improve quality of life\nPalliative Care\nBereavement\nDeath\nDiagnosis\nDisease \nManagement\nPalliative Care\nRehabilitation\nSurvivorship",
