    "text": "Section Vi: Pain Management And Palliative Care\n97\nAll components make up the whole person\n                      \nSuggestion: Caused by serious disease instead of cancer (under physical pain)\nPalliatice care package at each level of the healthcare system \nCo-morbid causes.\nPhysical\nCaused by treatment.\nCaused by cancer.\nLoss of role and \nsocial status\nLoss of job.\nFinancial concerns\nWorries about the future \nof family.\nDependency\nSocial\nPsycological\nTotal pain\nSpiritual\nAnxiety\nFear of suffering\nDepression\nPast \nexperience\nof illness\nAnger at fate/anger \nwith God\nLoss of faith\nFinding meaning\nFear of the unknown\nReferral Hospitals\n• Holistic assessment and reassessment\n• Appropriate pain and symptoms management.\n• Holistic care with specialized management (radiotherapy, chemotherapy, surgeon …)\nDistrict and \nProvincial Hospitals \n• Holistic assessment, reassessment \n• Appropriate pain and symptoms management\n• Initiate or adjust PC regimen for patients with mild, moderate, or severe symptoms.\n• Make plans for continued PC after the patient is discharged to lower level or to home. \n• Refer to referral hospitals for specialized management.\n• Patient’s visit at home during the first week after discharge and as needed.\n• Holistic pain assessment\n• Pain and symptoms management using the WHO pain management Ladder.\n• Provide emotional support.\n• Supervise CHWs who visit patients at home with palliative care needs.\n• Request for oral morphine solution for PC patient under HC catchment area\n• Request advice from district level \n• Refer to the district level for complicated cases.\nHealth Center\n• Recognize and report:\n    > Inadequately relieved pain or other physical, psychological, or social distress\n    > Improper use of morphine or other medicines\n• Provide emotional support.\n• Educate family on daily patient care including feeding, hygiene, mobility, medications.\nHome",
