    "text": "Section Vi: Pain Management And Palliative Care\n98\nCommon symptoms in palliative care and management\nFigure 48:  Algorithm for common symptoms causes and management in Palliative Care\nEnd of life care\nCare rendered to individuals who are near death or for whom death is expected in a relatively finite period of \ntime. It includes supportive care, palliative care, hospice care.\nPrinciple:\n•\t\nMost patients find taking medication a burden especially towards the end of life.\n•\t\nFocus on giving medication that will improve the patient’s quality of life and discontinue any unneces­\nsary medications.\nPain\nConstipation\nNausea & Vomiting\nWounds\nBreathlessness\nDelirium\n• Holistic pain assessment\n• Holistic care\n• Consider non-pharmacological treatment.\n• Use WHO Analgesic ladder for physical pain.\n• Holistic assessment\n• Treat underlying causes\n• Consider nonpharmacological treatment:\n    > Encourage fluid intake.\n    > Increase fibre in diet.\n    > Encourage exercise where possible.\n• Pharmacological(laxative)\n• Holistic assessment\n• Treat underlying cause\n• Consider nonpharmacological treatment.\n• Treat with anti-emetic\n    > Metoclopramide (10-20) mg every 8 hours and \n       30min before meal)\n    > Ondansetron 8mg every 12 hours day \n    > Haloperidol (1,25-2,5) mg\n• For toxins use dexamethasone 8-16mg OD\n• Holistic assessment\n• Correct underlying cause if possible.\n• Clean and dress the wound daily using Normal saline.\n• If it is Malodour apply metronidazole powder \n   (tablets crushed).\n• Analgesic according to pain assessment use WHO \n   ANALGESIC\n• Appropriate antibiotic if necessary\n• Palliative surgery, chemotherapy, radiotherapy\n• Reassure the patient.\n• Breathing exercises and relaxation techniques \n• Find the most comfortable position for the patient.\n• Ensure good ventilation.\n• Treat underlying causes for breathlessness.\n• Low dose morphine 2.5 to 5mg in 4hours\n• Diazepam 2.5-5mg po up to tds 