    "conditions": [
      "pregnancy"
    ],
    "content_type": "emergency_protocol",
    "char_length": 543,
    "word_count": 90
  },
  {
    "id": 172,
    "text": "13\n1.2.1.1.6 Medications  \no Ask the patient what medications they are taking \no Ask if they are taking or have taken any of the following \nmedicines now or in the past: \n Lasix \no If the patient is symptomatic, this may suggest the \nneed for intravenous therapy.   \no Excessive diuresis may cause volume depletion and \nreduce blood flow to the kidneys. \n B-Blockers \no May mask tachycardia if a patient is in a heart failure \nexacerbation. \n Ace-Inhibitors \no May cause or worsen acute renal injury. If the patient \nis taking, you will need to check the urine output and \ncreatinine. \n1.2.1.2 Social History \n1.  Ask about the following: \nAlcohol \no How many drinks do you have each day, week?   \no How many years have you been drinking alcohol?  \nTobacco \no Do you smoke or chew tobacco? \no How many cigarettes do you smoke every day? \no How many years have you smoked? \n \nListen for drugs that cause volume depletion or \nacute kidney injury, increase the serum \npotassium, or suppress the heart rate.",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
