    "id": 203,
    "text": "44\n2.2.6.1 Hypertensive Emergency \nBP > 180/110 with evidence to damage to brain, eye, heart, kidneys \nor fetus  \n1. Give medication every 30 minutes \n2. Call physician and admit to hospital \n3. Check blood pressure every thirty minutes until transfer \n***DO NOT LOWER THE BLOOD PRESSURE MORE THAN 25%*** \nMedication \nDosing \nNotes \nCaptopril \n25 mg orally \nContraindicated in pregnancy and \nrenal failure (Cr≥µmol/L) \nNifedipine \n(immediate release) \n10 mg orally \n \nHydralazine \n25 mg orally or \n20mg IV \n \nFurosemide  \n40 mg orally or \n20mg IV \nIf \nevidence \nof \npulmonary \ncongestion \n2.2.6.2 Treat essential Hypertension \nSTAGE 1 (BP 140/90 – 159/99) WITHOUT RISK FACTORS \nEncourage lifestyle modifications  \nIf unable to achieve a blood pressure < 140/90 in 12 months, start \none antihypertensive \nMonitor every 3 months",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
