  },
  {
    "id": 222,
    "text": "63\n \nCriteria for ARF diagnosis according to WHO \no The first episode of ARF can be confirmed if: \no 2 MAJOR, or 1 MAJOR and 2 MINOR manifestations are present \nplus there is evidence of preceding Group A streptococcal \ninfection. \no Recurrent ARF (with no RHD) can be confirmed if \no 2 MAJOR, or 1 MAJOR and 2 MINOR manifestations are present \nplus there is evidence of preceding Group A streptococcal \ninfection. \no Recurrent ARF (with existing RHD) can be confirmed if \no 2 MINOR manifestations are present plus there is evidence of \npreceding Group A streptococcal infection. \nComplication \nRheumatic heart disease \nInvestigations \no Throat swab for culture (positive throat culture of group A \nStreptoccocal infection) \no Raised ASOT/ASLO antibodies titre (Anti-streptolysin-0-titre –\nASOT of 1:300) \no Anti DNase B \no FBC/ ESR/CRP \no Chest x-ray – features of cardiomegaly \no ECG \no Echocardiogram \nManagement \nPersons with symptoms of ARF should be hospitalized to ensure \naccurate diagnosis, and to receive clinical care and education about \npreventing further episodes of ARF.",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 65,
    "conditions": [
      "general"
    ],
    "content_type": "definition_criteria",
    "char_length": 1085,
    "word_count": 170
  },
  {
    "id": 223,
    "text": "64\n \nThe diagnosis should include an initial echocardiogram used to help \nidentify and measure heart valve damage. \nLong-term preventative management should be organized before \ndischarge. \nAll cases of ARF should receive: \no A single injection of Benzathine penicillin G \n(Extencilline):25,000–50,000 units/kg/dose, maximum 1.2 mega \nunits dose \n Or \no Oral Penicillin (Pen V) 25–50mg/kg/day in divided 3 doses for 10 \ndays Or (Erythromycin 30-50mg/kg/day divided in 3 doses if \npenicillin allergy) \nSymptomatic Treatment \nArthritis and fever \no Aspirin 75–100mg/kg/day in 4–6 divided doses. Continue \ntreatment until fever and joint inflammation are controlled and \nthen gradually reduced over a 2-week period. Add an antacid to \nreduce risk of gastric irritation \no Prednisolone 1-2mg OD for 2 weeks then taper for 2 weeks with \ngood response begin \no Aspirin in the 3rd week and continue until 8th week tapering in \nthe final 2 weeks \nChorea \no Most mild-moderate cases do not need medication \no Provide calm and supportive environment (prevent accidental \nself-harm) \no For severe cases: Carbamazepine per os",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 66,
    "conditions": [
      "general"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 1113,
    "word_count": 166
  },
  {
    "id": 224,
    "text": "65\n \no <6 years: 10-20mg/kg/day divided in 3 doses \no 6-12 years: 400-800mg/day divided in 3 doses \no >12 years: 200mg x 2/day \nOR \nValproic acid 20-30mg/kg/day divided in 2 doses; Duration: \n2 weeks \nCarditis \no Bed rest if in cardiac failure \no Anti-failure medication as above \no Anti-coagulation medication if atrial fibrillation is present \no Management plan when the acute episode is controlled \nadminister the first dose of secondary prophylaxis \no Register the individual with the local health authority or RHD \nProgram \no Provide disease education for the person with ARF and the \nfamily \no Understanding of ARF and RHD and risks of ARF recurrence \no Importance of regular secondary prophylaxis and medical \nreview \no Recognizing own signs and symptoms of ARF and RHD \no Risks associated with future RHD (e.g. pregnancy, surgery and \nhigh level of aftercare) \no Importance of dental health \no Include an ARF diagnosis alert on computer systems and/or \nmedical files (if applicable) \no Refer to local health facility for ongoing management \no Arrange dental review (and provide advice about endocarditis \nprevention)",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 67,
    "conditions": [
      "general"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 1124,
    "word_count": 177
  },
  {
    "id": 225,
    "text": "66\n \nLong-term Management \no Regular secondary prophylaxis (Recommended Secondary \nProphylaxis Regimen) \no Regular medical review \no Regular dental review \no Echocardiogram (if available) following each episode of ARF, \nand routine echocardiogram: \no Every 2 years for children (sooner if there is evidence of cardiac \nsymptoms) \nSecondary prophylaxis \no Prevents the occurrence of GAS infections which can lead to \nrecurrent ARF \no Reduces the severity of RHD (and can result in cure of RHD after \nmany years) \no Helps prevent death from severe RHD \no Secondary prophylaxis is indicated for people who have: \no ARF confirmed by the Jones Criteria \no RHD confirmed on echocardiogram \no ARF or RHD not confirmed, but highly suspected \no Dosage \no Benzathine Penicillin G IM every 4 weeks \no 1,200,000 units for ALL people ≥30kg \no 600,000 units for children <30kg \no Penicillin V if injections not tolerated or contraindicated \no 250mg oral, twice-daily for all children \no Erythromycin if proven allergy to Penicillin: 250mg oral, twice-\ndaily for ALL people.",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 68,
    "conditions": [
      "paediatric"
    ],
    "content_type": "definition_criteria",
    "char_length": 1059,
    "word_count": 166
  },
  {
    "id": 226,
    "text": "67\n \nTable 1: Recommended duration of Secondary Prophylaxis \nDisease Classification \nDuration of Secondary \nProphylaxis \nARF with No proven carditis \nMinimum of 5 years after last \nARF, or Until age 18 years \n(whichever is longer) \nMild-moderate RHD \n(or healed carditis) \nMinimum 10 years after last \nARF, or - Until age 25 years \n(whichever is longer) \nSevere \nRHD \nand \nfollowing \nCardiac Surgery for RHD \nContinue medication for life \n3.2 Rheumatic Heart Disease \nDefinition \nIt is an inflammatory damage of the heart valves, as a complication \nof acute rheumatic fever. The mitral valve is the most commonly \ninvolved valve, although any valve may be affected. \nTypes of valvular lesions \no Mitral regurgitation/stenosis \no Aortic regurgitation/stenosis \no Tricuspid regurgitation \no Mixed regurgitation and stenosis \no Multivalvular heart diseases \nSigns and symptoms \no May be asymptomatic when minor lesions \no Heart murmurs over affected valve",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 69,
    "conditions": [
      "emergency"
    ],
    "content_type": "definition_criteria",
    "char_length": 952,
    "word_count": 140
  },
  {
    "id": 227,
    "text": "68\n \nComplications \no Congestive cardiac failure with pulmonary oedema \no Bacterial endocarditis \nInvestigations \no Chest x-ray \no ECG \no Echocardiography \nManagement \no Treat underlying complication, e.g., heart failure, pulmonary \noedema \no Continue prophylaxis against recurrent rheumatic fever \no Ensure oral hygiene \no Endocarditis prophylaxis if dental procedures, urinary tract \ninstrumentation, and GIT manipulations \nProcedure done above the diaphragm \no Amoxicillin 50mg/kg (Max 2gr) 1 hour before the procedure \n \nOr \no Erythromycin 50mg/kg (max 1.5gr) – if allergic toPenicillins \nBelow the diaphragm \no Ampicillin 50mg/kg IV or IM (max 2gr) withGentamycine, \n2mg/kg (max 120mg) 30minutes before the procedure \nThen \no Amoxycillin per os 25mg/kg (max1gr) 6 hours after the \nprocedure \nEnsure good follow up by cardiologist",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 70,
    "conditions": [
      "monitoring"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 834,
    "word_count": 115
  },
  {
    "id": 228,
    "text": "69\n \n3.3 Cardiomyopathy \n3.3.1 DILATED CARDYOMIOPATHY \nDefinition: \nDilated cardiomyopathy refers to a group of conditions of diverse \netiology in which both ventricles are dilated with reduced \ncontractility. \nClassification \nClassification based on the predominant structural and functional \nabnormalities \no Dilated Cardiomyopathy: primarily systolic dysfunction \no Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy: primarily diastolic dysfunction \no Restrictive Cardiomyopathy: primarily diastolic but often \ncombined with systolic dysfunction \nCauses \no Infections (e.g. Viral+++, Rickettsia, Chagas disease) \no Neuromuscular disorders (e.g. Duchenne dystrophy, Becker \ndystrophy) \no Endocrine, metabolic and nutritional (e.g. hyperthyroidism, \nFatty acid oxidation disorders, beriberi, kwashiorkor) \no Diseases of coronary arteries (e.g. Kawasaki, Aberrant Left \nCoronary Artery - ALCAPA) \no Autoimmune diseases (e.g. Rheumatic carditis, juvenile \nrheumatoid arthritis, systemic lupus erythematosus, \ndermatomyositis, systemic lupus erythematosus) \no Drugs toxicity (e.g. doxorubicin, cyclophosphamide, IPECA) \no Hematologic diseases (e.g. anemia, Sickle cell anemia, \nhypereosinophilic syndrome Löffler syndrome)",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 71,
    "conditions": [
      "hypertension"
    ],
    "content_type": "definition_criteria",
    "char_length": 1198,
    "word_count": 137
  },
  {
    "id": 229,
    "text": "70\n \nSigns and symptoms \nSee signs of congestive heart failure \nDiagnosis \no ECG: proeminent P wave, LV or RV hypertrophy, nonspecific T-\nwave abnormalities \no Chest X-ray: cardiomegaly, pulmonary edema \no Echocardiogram: confirm diagnosis and shows LA and LV \ndilation, poor contractility \no FBC, Urea and creatinine, Electrolytes (Na, K) \no Myocardial biopsy, PCR \nManagement \n- Treatment: (Refer to principles and medication of congestive heart \nfailure) \n3.3.2 HYPERTROPHIC CARDIOMYOPATHY \nCauses \no Left ventricle obstruction (Coartation of aorta, hypertension, \naortic stenosis) \no Secondary (infants of diabetic mothers, corticosteroids in \npremature infants) \no Metabolic (Glycogen storage disease type II (Pompe disease) \no Familiar hypertrophic cardiomyopathy \no Syndroms (Beckwith - Wiedmansyndrom, Friedereich, ataxia)",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 72,
    "conditions": [
      "diabetes",
      "monitoring"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 830,
    "word_count": 110
  },
  {
    "id": 230,
    "text": "71\n \nSigns and Symptoms \no Weakness \no Fatigue \no Dyspnea on effort \no Palpitations \no Angina pectoris \no Dizziness and syncope \no Increased risk of sudden death \nDiagnosis \no ECG: LV hypertrophy \no Chest X-ray: Mild cardiomegaly \no Echocardiogram: LV hypertrophy, ventricular outflow tract \ngradient \no Doppler flow studies may demonstrate diastolic dysfunction \nbefore the development of hypertrophy \nManagement \no Prohibit competitive sports and strenuous physical activities \no Propranolol 0.5 -1mg/kg/day devised in 3 doses or Atenolol \no Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator if documented \narrhythmias or a history of unexplained syncope \no Open heart surgery for septal myotomy: rarely indicated \n3.3.3 RESTRICTIVE CARDIOMYOPATHY \nDefinition \nRestrictive cardiomyopathy refers to a group of disorders in which \nthe heart chambers are unable to properly fill with blood because \nof stiffness in the heart muscle. Its prognosis is poor, and clinical \ndeterioration can be rapid.",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 73,
    "conditions": [
      "general"
    ],
    "content_type": "definition_criteria",
    "char_length": 985,
    "word_count": 139
  },
  {
    "id": 231,
    "text": "72\n \nCauses \no Idiopathic, Systemic disease (scleroderma, amyloidosis, or \no sarcoidosis) \no Mucopolysaccharidosis \no Hypereosinophilic syndrome; malignancies \no Radiation therapy  \no Isolated non compaction of the left ventricular myocardium \n \nSigns and symptoms \no Dyspnea \no Edema and ascites \no Hepatomegaly with increased venous pressure \no Pulmonary congestion \n \nComplications \no Arrhythmias \no Mitral regurgitation \no Progressive heart failure \no Tricuspid regurgitation \n \nInvestigations \no ECG: Prominent P waves, ST segment depression, T-wave \ninversion \no Chest X-ray: mild to moderate cardiomegaly \no Echocardiogram: markedly enlarged atria and small to \nnormalsized ventricles with often preserved systolic function \nbut highly abnormal diastolic function \n \nManagement \no Lasix 2mg/kg divided in 2 doses \no Aldactone 1-2mg/kg devised in 2 doses \no Antiarrhythmic agents / biventricular pacing are used as \nrequired \no Aspirin or Warfarin in case of non compaction LV with an \nincreased risk of mural thrombosis and stroke \no Cardiac transplantation where possible and indicated",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 74,
    "conditions": [
      "hypertension"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 1093,
    "word_count": 149
  },
  {
    "id": 232,
    "text": "73\n \n4 CARDIAC \nSURGERY \nAND \nPOST-OP \nMANAGEMENT GUIDELINES \n4.1 Cardiac surgery indications, complications and \nfollow up \nCommon Congenital Heart Defects For Surgery \no Ventriculo-septal defect (VSD): a defect between the two \nventricles \no Atrio-septal defect (ASD): a hole between the two atria  \no Atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD)  \no Patent ductus arteriosous (PDA): communication between the \naorta and the pulmonary artery \no Tetralogy of Fallot: Several defects including a VSD, pulmonary \nhypoplasia and stenosis  \no Coarctation of  aorta \no Pulmonary valve stenosis  \no Aortic valve stenosis",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 75,
    "conditions": [
      "general"
    ],
    "content_type": "general_guideline",
    "char_length": 608,
    "word_count": 85
  },
  {
    "id": 233,
    "text": "74\n \n \nAcquired cardio-vasculaires diseases \no Rheumatic Heart Diseases \no MR, MS, AoR… \no Coronary diseases and other vascular diseases \no Atherosclerotic diseases, aneurysm, dissection… \no Degenerative heart diseases \no Arrythmias( Heart Block, AF…)",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
