  },
  {
    "id": 234,
    "text": "75\n \n4.2 Types of cardiac Interventions and valve types \nTypes of cardiac interventions \no Open heart surgery with or without Cardio-pulmonary bypass \n(congenital and acquired heart diseases including valve surgery) \no Closed heart surgery (PDA ligation, coarctation repair…) \no Catheterization (balloon valvuloplasty, device and stent \nimplantation…) \nTypes of Valve Surgery \no Valve Repair = Fixing the damaged heart valve (either making it \nopen better or close better) without having to put any foreign \nmaterial into the heart. \no Valve Replacement = Introducing a prosthetic valve to take the \nplace of the damaged valve \no Mechanical \no Made of metal: Lasts a long time, Requires anticoagulation \n(warfarin) management for life to prevent clot formation and \nvalve thrombosis(death) \no Bioprosthetic \no Made of tissue (pig or cow) Does not last very long (3-10 years) \nand most patients will require a second operation. No \nanticoagulation required",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 77,
    "conditions": [
