  },
  {
    "id": 279,
    "text": "128\n \nBG (Fingerstick Blood Glucose) > 400mg/dL\nTransfer to District Hospital\nF\nBG 200-400 mg/dL with danger signs\nTransfer to District Hospital\nFBG 200-400 mg/dL without danger signs\nManage as Outpatient\nDANGER SIGNS:\n• Dehydration\n• Abdominal pain \nwith \nnausea/vomiting\n• Hypotension\n• Slow & deep \nbreathing\n• Confusion\n \n6.2.6 PLAN \nCONDITIONS THAT REQURE DIFFERENT MANAGEMENT \nPregnancy \n \nPregnant women should be started on insulin immediately. They should NOT \nbe on oral agents (glibenclamide or metformin) or ace-Inhibitors. \nAll women of reproductive age should be referred for family planning. \nRenal \nFailure  \nStop metformin and sulfonylurea if creatinine doubles or > 150 μmol/L  \nDecrease insulin by 25% if  \nCreatinine doubles or  \n> 150 μmol/L and patient has evidence of hypoglycemia \nACE-Inhibitors (Ace-i) \nIf Cr > 200umol/L, then ACE-I are contraindicated \nIf Cr increases by 50% hold ACE-I.  Re-check Cr within 1 month. \nLiver \nFailure \n \nIf patient has evidence of hypoglycemia, then decrease patient’s insulin by \n25%. \nHIV \nPositive  \nBe sure to refer to ID clinic because patient may need ARVs changed. \nCAUTION!!  Take note of these situations where \nstandard therapies are contraindicated, before \nproceeding!",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
    "page": 130,
    "conditions": [
      "diabetes",
      "pregnancy"
    ],
    "content_type": "treatment_recommendation",
    "char_length": 1239,
    "word_count": 182
  },
  {
    "id": 280,
    "text": "129\n \n6.2.6.1 Emergencies  \nDKA or Random Blood Glucose > 400  \no Bolus 1 liter normal saline. \no Give regular insulin 10 units. \no Check FBG every hour. \no Repeat insulin 10 units for FBC >300mg/dL until transfer to the district hospital. \nHypoglycemia (Adults) \no Give by oral route of rapid sugar( juices, soda,banana…) \no Give IV glucose 50% solution(if a patient is unable to follow command) \no Check FBGevery 1-2 hours. \no Repeat IV glucose 50% for FBG < 70 , transfer  patient to the district hospital if \nhypoglycemia is persisting after 30 minutes of initial management \n6.2.6.2 Insulin Therapy \nIndications for insulin: \no Type 1 or malnutrition type diabetes \no DKA or glucose >400mg/dL \no Type 2 DM patients already on maximum oral therapy \no Pregnancy \no Renal (>150mmol/L)  \no Children < 18 years old \nIf not indicated, go to \nOral Therapy.",
    "source": "IMB-NCDs-guideline",
